[1] Case update
- Mon 27 Aug 2018. Epidemiological situation report, 26 Aug 2018, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., edited]
https://mailchi.mp/4b1528882fd6/ebola_kivu_27aout?e=f27b7f5a19

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 26 Aug 2018:
- A total of 111 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, 83 confirmed and 28 probable.
- Of the 83 confirmed cases, 18 are cured, 18 are hospitalized, and 47 have died.
- 10 suspected cases are under investigation.
- No new cases confirmed.
- 4 new people healed, including 3 care providers.
- 3 confirmed cases, including 1 in Beni and 2 in Mabalako.
- 2445 contacts to follow

News of the response
Social mobilization
-------------------
- Following the community's latest protests against the Ebola response, the coordination organized a meeting with the mayor, notables, customary chiefs, district leaders, cell leaders, youth movements, and civil society from the city of Beni [North Kivu]. More than 350 people attended an exclusive information session on Ebola with the coordinators of the response. During this session that lasted nearly 4.5 hours, those present were able to ask all the questions and share their concerns. This exchange helped to ease tensions within the community. At the end of the session, the authorities committed themselves to preparing an action plan to support the different components of the response, in particular the signaling of alerts, the follow-up of contacts, and dignified and secure burials.

Vaccination
-----------
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 4130 people have been vaccinated, including 1992 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 1000 in Beni [North Kivu], 1017 in Mandima [Ituri province], and 121 in Oicha [North Kivu].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[It would be informative to read what were the issues of concern for the community regarding the follow-up of contacts and signaling of alerts. It is hopeful that the steps being taken to reassure relatives their deceased family members are being treated with respect, will improve their sense of their cultural customs being honored. - Mod.LK]

- Mon 27 Aug 2018. As Ebola cases hit 111, DRC responders address local concerns.
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy), edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/08/ebola-cases-hit-111-drc-responders-address-local-concerns
[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) health ministry reported 8 more lab-confirmed Ebola cases over the past 4 days, along with another probable infection, all from areas that have already reported illnesses.

[...]

The newly confirmed cases are from Mabalako, the health zone that includes the hot spot city of Mangina, as well as Beni and Oicha [North Kivu], where an illness was confirmed in a physician last week [week of 20 Aug 2018] and where at least 2 more suspected cases were reported.

The new developments push the overall outbreak total to 111 cases, including 83 confirmed and 28 probable cases. 9 more deaths were reported, raising that total to 72. Health officials are investigating 10 suspected cases, according to the ministry's update today [27 Aug 2018].

The World Health Organization (WHO) in a 24 Aug 2018 update provided some epidemiologic details about the patients sickened in the outbreak so far.

Of 88 confirmed and probable cases reported as of 19 Aug 2018, the median age is 32 years old, with an age range of 0-74 years. Adults ages 30-39 account for 28 percent (25) of the cases. Of all cases, 58 percent (51) are female. Earlier in the outbreak, WHO officials had said responders were seeing a higher-than-expected number of illnesses in women and children.

Illness onsets range from late April to 13 Aug 2018, according to the WHO.

[...]

Last week [week of 20 Aug 2018], media outlets reported that angry youth burned a health center in the village of Manbangu [North Kivu] where Ebola vaccine was given. A health ministry spokeswoman told Reuters that an incident took place at the clinic, but that it hadn't been burned.

The DRC's health ministry said health teams have closed and disinfected a clinic in Beni after it reported 3 Ebola cases, 2 confirmed and 1 probable, according to its 25 Aug 2018 update. It said the steps are geared toward curbing transmission to other people and health workers.

Several health workers have been infected in the outbreak in Mangina and Beni, many of whom were thought to have been exposed to sick patients before the outbreak was declared.

Health workers are known to amplify the spread of the disease, and outbreak response teams have removed staff from at least 2 facilities so that potentially exposed health workers can be quarantined and monitored for any symptoms.

[...]

In its recent update, the WHO said 7160 more vaccine doses arrived in Kinshasa on 20 Aug 2018 and were immediately sent to Beni. It added that it expected that an additional 2160 doses would be shipped by the end of the week.

Push for vaccinating pregnant women
-----------------------------------
[See [3] below re- commentary in STAT Morning Rounds newsletter, 27 Aug 2018.]

[...]

The group also noted that at least 20 pregnant women were unintentionally vaccinated in a previous trial, with no evidence of harm. They urged health leaders to apply the recent WHO rationale for using yellow fever vaccine -- which also contains live vaccine virus -- for pregnant women.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

