[3] Vaccination and antivirals
- Mon 27 Aug 2018. Pregnant women should be eligible for experimental Ebola vaccine, experts argue.
[STAT Morning Rounds newsletter; summary provided by Greg Folkers]
https://www.statnews.com/2018/08/27/ebola-vaccine-pregnant-lactating-women/

The decision to exclude pregnant and lactating women from an effort to vaccinate people exposed to Ebola in the current outbreak is wrong and should be reversed, 3 public health experts write in a new opinion piece for STAT. Here's what you need to know:

The context: There's an experimental vaccine available that's been shown the be effective against the strain of Ebola in the outbreak. Health officials have launched a vaccination program to try to stem the spread of the virus, but pregnant and lactating women aren't allowed to receive the vaccine.

The decision: Health officials in the Democratic Republic of the Congo made that decision based on the advice of 2 expert panels that offer guidance on the use of experimental Ebola therapies.

The counterargument: The experts say it's indefensible to deny pregnant and lactating women the experimental vaccine, given that the fatality rate is 80 percent or higher for pregnant women who contract Ebola and nearly all survivors miscarry. "There's no question that evidence about the safety of the Ebola vaccine in pregnancy is limited. But what we don't know is dwarfed by what we do know," Ruth Faden, Ruth Karron, and Carleigh Krubiner write.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
from
Greg Folkers
NIAID, NIH
<gfolkers@nih.gov>

[It really is a risk-benefit question in the middle of an outbreak. The vaccine is not likely to cause greater harm that what already exists, as it is known that pregnant women and babies suffer severe outcomes following infection. As stated above, the fatality rate is 80 percent or higher for pregnant women who contract Ebola and nearly all survivors miscarry. See report above in [1]. Pregnant women were vaccinated inadvertently in the West African outbreak without complications being reported. Therefore, the decision not to vaccinate them should be reconsidered. Giving birth or a miscarriage while infected presents a tremendous hazard to the healthcare workers attending the birth and the families. - Mod.LK]

- Mon 27 Aug 2018. Recovery from Ebola.
[Digital Congo; in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.digitalcongo.net/article/5b83fed1218124000402f4f9/

According to the epidemiological situation presented by the Ministry of Health, a total of 14 people were cured of Ebola in the territory of Beni, in the province of North Kivu where the 10th epidemic of this virus was declared.

In its latest newsletter released Sat night, the Congolese Ministry of Health announced the healing of 14 people who contracted Ebola in the Beni region

[...]

"Congratulations to these survivors and the DRC Ministry of Health for making large-scale experimental Ebola treatments available during an epidemic -- a world first and a beacon of hope for people with the disease. We are proudly your partners," reacted on his Twitter account Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, director of the World Health Organization, WHO.

Returning to the hygiene and sanitation pillar, one of the measures on which the Ministry of Health relies to eradicate this epidemic, the press release announces that a hygiene team has proceeded to the disinfection and closing of a dispensary in the Beni health zone after the latter reported 3 cases, 2 confirmed and 1 probable. "The Committee on Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) and Biosafety is the commission responsible for measures to stop the transmission of infectious diseases to other people and health workers," writes the document, adding that the structure deals in particular with the distribution of personal protective equipment to health workers, the installation of chlorinated water points, and the disinfection of households and health facilities.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[It is not clear whether these individuals were cured through the use of mAb114. If so, it would be helpful to know what proportion of trials of this antibody have been successful; however it may be premature to evaluate its success because of different timing of the treatment, severity of the symptoms, age of the patient, and more. - Mod.LK]

